items: Net Water Uptake (NWU) Breakthrough: New regulatory-cleared AI tools now calculate NWU from standard NCCT to refine thrombectomy selection for "low ASPECTS" patients; high NWU is linked to poorer outcomes despite recanalization.
MeVO Triage Superiority: Head-to-head data shows specialized AI algorithms achieving 92.3% sensitivity for Medium Vessel Occlusions (MeVO), compared to just 17.3% in conventional models.

Door-to-Notification Slash: Real-world data across 100+ hospitals shows AI integration reduces median door-to-notification time by 22 minutes (43%) for LVOs and 33 minutes (45%) for neurosurgical ICH consults.
Alzheimer‚Äôs "Blood Clock": A new single blood test model uses amyloid and tau accumulation patterns to predict the exact onset timeframe of clinical symptoms years in advance.
Multiple Sclerosis Durability: Five-year data published in JAMA Neurology for Ublituximab (Briumvi) shows a sustained annualized relapse rate of 0.020‚Äîroughly one relapse every 50 years.
Agentic AI Pilots: Pilot programs in the US and UK are now deploying "Agentic AI" that autonomously triages neurology referrals, reducing patient wait times by an estimated 30-40%.

articles.title: Prediction of hemorrhagic transformation after intravenous thrombolysis in acute anterior circulation ischemic stroke through radiomics-based machine learning models
articles.summary: This study utilized a cohort of 254 acute ischemic stroke patients to develop machine learning models capable of predicting hemorrhagic transformation (HT) following intravenous thrombolysis. By extracting 1,874 radiomic features‚Äîincluding shape, first-order statistics, and high-order textures‚Äîfrom pre-treatment NCCT scans, the researchers identified 26 key "nonzero" coefficients that define a patient‚Äôs bleed risk. The resulting Logistic Regression (LR) model was the most stable, achieving an AUC of 0.814 in external validation. This suggests that the standard CT, often viewed as a simple tool to rule out existing blood, actually contains complex spatial data that reflects the underlying integrity of the blood-brain barrier.
articles.clinicalContext: HT is a major risk that complicates the decision to use thrombolytics. This study shows that standard-of-care NCCT contains "invisible" textures that can objectively identify patients at high risk for bleeding more reliably than visual inspection alone.
articles.myTake: We‚Äôve all had those "borderline" cases where we hesitate to give tPA. This tool suggests we can use the data already in our standard CTs to add a layer of objective safety to those high-stakes ER decisions.

articles.title: Predicting onset of symptomatic Alzheimer ºs disease with plasma p-tau217 clocks
articles.summary: A landmark study in Nature Medicine (February 2026) introduced a "biological clock" that predicts the onset of Alzheimer‚Äôs symptoms with a median margin of error of only 3 to 3.7 years. By measuring the ratio of phosphorylated to non-phosphorylated tau (%p-tau217) in blood plasma, researchers found that this biomarker follows a highly consistent and predictable trajectory as the disease progresses. The study validated this "clock" across five different commercial assays, proving that the model is robust enough for wide-scale clinical lab use.
articles.clinicalContext: The most critical clinical finding is that the window between biomarker positivity and symptom onset shrinks significantly as patients age. For a person who becomes "tau positive" at age 60, the median time to symptoms is roughly 20 years; however, for someone who hits that same threshold at age 80, the transition typically occurs in just over 11 years. This suggests that while younger brains may have more cognitive resilience, older brains likely face "co-pathologies" that accelerate decline, making age a vital factor in risk stratification.
articles.myTake: This is the "how long do I have?" tool we‚Äôve been waiting for. Instead of just telling a patient they‚Äôre "positive" for Alzheimer‚Äôs markers, we can now provide a data-driven timeline based on their specific p-tau217 levels and age. It‚Äôs a huge step forward for family planning and helps us identify exactly when to start therapies to get the maximum benefit before symptoms even emerge.

article.title: Spotlight: Deep Learning-Based Epileptic Seizure Detection from EEG Signals and PPG signals Using LSTM and CNN Models
article.summary: This study introduces a hybrid deep learning framework that combines Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) for spatial feature extraction with Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks for temporal modeling. Unlike traditional models that rely solely on EEG, this system integrates synchronized Photoplethysmogram (PPG) data to capture autonomic fluctuations and heart rate variability associated with ictogenesis. The model was validated on multimodal datasets, achieving a peak accuracy of 99.6%, an F1-score of 99.72%, and a Cohen‚Äôs Kappa of 98%, significantly outperforming traditional machine learning classifiers like XGBoost and Random Forest.
article.clinicalContext: Continuous EEG monitoring remains the gold standard but is often limited by the need for specialized expertise and the difficulty of long-term application in non-clinical settings. By incorporating PPG‚Äîa modality easily captured by wearable sensors‚Äîthis framework compensates for "subtle or ambiguous" EEG signatures. This multimodal approach provides a secondary layer of physiological validation, reducing false alarms and improving the robustness of real-time seizure detection for at-home patient monitoring.
article.myTake: This research is a great example of how we can move beyond single-stream data by using "black box" deep learning to fuse cortical and autonomic signals. It‚Äôs an exciting step toward building reliable, real-time wearable tools that help us monitor our patients more accurately outside of the hospital.

1f771c42-a3d9-4eb1-8850-7049518076b7.heading: To Use Your Brain, First Accept The Terms And Conditions: Legal Protections For Commercial Brain-Computer Interfaces
1f771c42-a3d9-4eb1-8850-7049518076b7.subheading: As AI begins to interface directly with the brain, legal protections for mental privacy and cognitive autonomy are moving from theory into law.
1f771c42-a3d9-4eb1-8850-7049518076b7.leftContent:
Your Brain Data Isn‚Äôt Just ‚ÄúAnother Signal‚Äù
As brain-computer interfaces and AI-assisted neurotechnology move into real clinical use, lawmakers are beginning to treat neural data as something fundamentally different‚Äîmore personal, more sensitive, and more legally protected than traditional health data.

From Ethics to Law
What was once discussed as ‚Äúneuroethics‚Äù is rapidly becoming enforceable regulation, with growing recognition of concepts like mental privacy and cognitive liberty‚Äîthe right to control how one‚Äôs thoughts and brain signals are accessed, interpreted, or altered.
1f771c42-a3d9-4eb1-8850-7049518076b7.rightContent:
Consent Is No Longer Implicit
Broad, boilerplate consent may not survive legal scrutiny as AI begins to decode cognitive states. Courts and regulators are signaling a move toward explicit, informed consent for neural data collection and AI interpretation.

Who‚Äôs Liable When AI Touches the Brain?
As AI systems influence cognition or behavior, responsibility becomes murky‚Äîbut liability often defaults to the human in the loop. Without clear governance, clinicians and institutions may carry more legal exposure than they expect.
1f771c42-a3d9-4eb1-8850-7049518076b7.clinicalPerspective: Neurology is entering an era where AI doesn‚Äôt just analyze images or notes‚Äîit interfaces with the brain itself. This article argues that future standards of care may depend not only on whether clinicians use neuro-AI tools, but on how deliberately they govern consent, oversight, and verification. For clinicians, the safest posture isn‚Äôt avoidance‚Äîit‚Äôs awareness.

474f56a7-5438-40b6-bd1e-b650c6c3b4a3.heading: Clinical Prompt Templates
474f56a7-5438-40b6-bd1e-b650c6c3b4a3.description: Click any prompt to copy it. Ready-to-use templates for common clinical AI scenarios.

templates.title: Generate Differential Diagnosis
templates.prompt: Act as a neurology attending. My patient is a [AGE] [SEX] presenting with [SYMPTOM] for [DURATION]. Key findings: [EXAM/LABS/IMAGING]. Generate a prioritized differential (top 5), with likelihood, supporting features, and one targeted investigation for each. Use evidence-based reasoning. Flag uncertainty. Do not fabricate data.
templates.useCase: Clinical reasoning support for complex presentations

templates.title: Discharge Summary Draft
templates.prompt: Act as a hospitalist writing a discharge summary. Patient: [NAME OMITTED], [AGE] [SEX], admitted [DATE] for [PRIMARY DIAGNOSIS]. Hospital course: [BRIEF SUMMARY]. Discharge condition: [STABLE/IMPROVED]. Write a structured discharge summary including: diagnosis, hospital course, discharge medications, follow-up instructions, and return precautions. Use clear patient-friendly language for the patient section.

templates.title: Evidence Summary
templates.prompt: Summarize the current evidence base for [INTERVENTION/DRUG/PROCEDURE] in patients with [CONDITION]. Include: level of evidence, key RCTs or meta-analyses, effect size, number needed to treat (if applicable), major contraindications, and areas of ongoing debate. Limit to 200 words. Cite uncertainty where evidence is weak. Do not fabricate citations.
templates.useCase: Quick evidence review at the point of care

templates.title: Patient Education Letter
templates.prompt: Write a patient education letter for a [AGE]-year-old with [DIAGNOSIS]. Explain: what the condition is, why it matters, the recommended treatment plan, what to expect, and when to seek urgent care. Use a 6th-grade reading level. Avoid medical jargon. End with 3 specific "warning signs" requiring immediate emergency evaluation.

templates.title: Neurophysiology Interpretation
templates.prompt: Act as a clinical neurophysiologist. Interpret the following EEG/EMG findings and generate a structured report: [PASTE FINDINGS]. Include: technical quality, relevant findings, clinical correlation, and impression. Note limitations. Flag any findings that warrant urgent clinical attention. Do not infer diagnoses beyond what the data supports.

templates.title: Research Abstract Summary
templates.prompt: Summarize this research paper for a clinical audience. Provide: (1) Study question in one sentence, (2) Study design and population, (3) Primary outcome and result, (4) Key limitations, (5) Clinical bottom line in one sentence. Keep total to 150 words. Do not overstate conclusions beyond what the study supports.
templates.useCase: Rapid journal club and literature scanning

22a721dd-bbb2-430e-bb2b-edcba440259b.definition: An autonomous or semi-autonomous AI system designed to use reasoning, memory, and external tools to achieve specific goals. Unlike standard "chat" models that simply predict the next word, an Agentic Model can plan multi-step workflows, interact with software (like a browser or database), and self-correct based on feedback from its environment.
22a721dd-bbb2-430e-bb2b-edcba440259b.relevance: In healthcare, agents represent a transition from "AI as a search engine" to "AI as a digital colleague." They can orchestrate complex clinical workflows‚Äîsuch as cross-referencing a new lab result with a patient's historical records, drafting a prior authorization, and scheduling a follow-up‚Äîreducing the cognitive load on clinicians and minimizing "click fatigue" in Electronic Health Records (EHR).
22a721dd-bbb2-430e-bb2b-edcba440259b.neurologyApplication: A Stroke Triage Agent could automatically monitor incoming imaging and EHR data; if it detects a potential Large Vessel Occlusion (LVO) on a CTA, it doesn't just "flag" it‚Äîit retrieves the patient's last known well time, checks for anticoagulant use, calculates the NIH Stroke Scale from the ER note, and alerts the neurointerventional team via a secure message with a summarized "pre-packaged" case file.

f5a52c8b-e417-4036-9b83-523805bb52c6.html:
Edition No. 2 | March 2026

Mission & Welcome

As we continue to navigate the rapid evolution of AI in medicine, we created The Neurology AI Pulse to provide a direct bridge between technical innovation and clinical practice. Our mission is to translate high-dimensional data and complex algorithms into actionable insights for the SIUH community and the broader neuroscientific field. Whether you are integrating these tools into your daily workflow or evaluating them from a distance, this newsletter is designed to keep you informed, critical, and prepared. From the latest in stroke triage to the ethics of generative models, we explore the intersection of machine learning and human neurology together.

‚Äî Yasir El-Sherif, MD, PhD (Practicing Neurologist) & Jai Shahani, MD (Neurologist in Training)

b5ff838a-b391-4885-a287-cce2d79d7abe.heading: SBAR-P Clinical AI Prompting Framework

steps.name: SITUATION
steps.description: State the clinical context clearly ‚Äî the care setting and presenting problem.
steps.example: 58-year-old female admitted with acute decompensated heart failure, EF 25%, currently on IV furosemide.

steps.name: BACKGROUND
steps.description: Provide relevant history, current medications, allergies, and key investigations.
steps.example: PMH: CKD stage 3 (eGFR 38), type 2 diabetes. Current Cr 2.1 (baseline 1.6). On metformin, lisinopril, carvedilol.

steps.name: ASK
steps.description: Be explicit about exactly what you want. Vague asks produce vague answers.
steps.example: List the top 5 causes of worsening renal function in this setting and the targeted workup for each.

steps.name: ROLE
steps.description: Assign a clinical persona to anchor the AI's frame of reference and reasoning style.
steps.example: Respond as a nephrology consultant reviewing this case and preparing a consultation note.

steps.name: PARAMETERS
steps.description: Set safety guardrails: specify the evidence base, require uncertainty disclosure, and define what to do when information is insufficient.
steps.example: Use current KDIGO 2024 guidelines. Explicitly flag any uncertainty. Do not fabricate lab values or medication doses.

b5ff838a-b391-4885-a287-cce2d79d7abe.templatePrompt:
Act as a [SPECIALTY] consultant reviewing this case.

Patient: [AGE] [SEX] presenting with [CHIEF COMPLAINT] for [DURATION].
Key findings: [VITAL SIGNS, EXAM FINDINGS, KEY LABS/IMAGING]
PMH: [RELEVANT COMORBIDITIES]
Current medications: [MED LIST]

Task: Generate a prioritized differential diagnosis (top 5 conditions).
For each diagnosis, provide:
  1. Likelihood assessment (High / Moderate / Low)
  2. Supporting clinical features from this case
  3. Single most informative next investigation

Requirements:
- Base reasoning on current evidence-based guidelines
- Explicitly flag areas of uncertainty
- Do not fabricate laboratory values, imaging findings, or medication doses
- If clinical information is insufficient, state what additional data is needed
safetyTips: Always verify AI-generated clinical reasoning against primary sources before acting.
Never submit patient-identifiable information (PHI) to consumer AI tools ‚Äî use only approved institutional platforms.
AI supports clinical judgment; it does not replace it. Final decisions remain with the treating clinician.
Document AI tool use in the medical record where institutional policy requires it.

c8ee40c4-980f-475c-864c-2368decd4cb2.title: The Turing Test
c8ee40c4-980f-475c-864c-2368decd4cb2.content: In 1950, Alan Turing published "Computing Machinery and Intelligence," proposing the Imitation Game as a practical test for machine intelligence. Rather than asking "Can machines think?" ‚Äî philosophically unanswerable ‚Äî Turing asked whether a machine could behave indistinguishably from a human in text conversation. This reframing from metaphysics to measurement shaped the next 70 years of AI development.
c8ee40c4-980f-475c-864c-2368decd4cb2.significance: The Turing Test established the behavioral benchmark for AI that still drives philosophical debate about machine consciousness, language, and cognition today.
